Buckle up buckaroo. We're pulling all the stops and heading off road, it's time for No Limit Vintage Cube.

No Limit Vintage is a 540 card powered+ cube, including the best of the best across Magic. This cube features Draft Matters, Ante, Silver Border, MTGO, MTGA, Heroes of the Realm, and Playtest cards to capture an absolutely max-power draft experience.

If you're already familiar with the MTGO Vintage Cube, this cube is kinda like that but if you cut the bottom 10% and replaced it with another top 10%. Vroom.

This cube is not friendly to inexperienced drafters. There's around a thousand keywords and a million combos (don't fact check that) alongside a lot of "what does this card do?" I still don't know how [[backup|b0dbcce3-d914-4e07-95a6-27a6b675ca38]] works and that's because [someone](https://cubecobra.com/user/view/e9b5f2a4-1c24-4e48-bec6-7243ad49901d) bought the version without reminder text.

While this cube proclaims "No Limit," it turns out there are a few limits. No Limit Vintage is designed to feel like a Vintage cube with additional powerful inclusions. It is not designed to feel like a silver border or conspiracy cube. When cards (or densities of cards) detract from Vintage Cube-esque gameplay, they can be cut. I will never cut a card on the basis of power level alone.

A full list of excluded cards is included at the bottom of the primer.

Thanks to [Maramas](https://cubecobra.com/user/view/5d6c2af1de02de1067366225) for [their article](https://cubecobra.com/content/article/602abb5969cb75105e271d4e) on writing a Cube primer. I stole most of it.

## Cube Principles

---

#### Cube Design

All cards that are designed and released by Wizards of the Coast are legal for consideration. They must be draftable in a standard Magic the Gathering sleeve ([[so no vanguards|5f92bfac-c4ad-4155-855e-cf330f2c8145]]). It must be possible for someone to own this cube if you had unlimited funds with [[one exception|e6d7fba8-a157-4d81-9d6b-bd210a96b248]], meaning most MTGA / MTGO exclusive cards cannot be included unless they receive [[a special printing|4f095067-cf24-4061-8626-dc68a66a0b36]].

Macro-archetype viability is an important aspect of this cube. All of aggro, midrange, control, combo, and tempo should be viable high-level choices.

Colour equality is another important aspect of this cube. I want players to be incentivized to explore the full range of the colour pie.

Not all games need to be fair and balanced. The ability for decks in No Limit to utterly high-roll the opponent into the dirt is a feature, not a bug. This cube celebrates the broken.

This is not a pure singleton cube. Inspired by my friend Eve, there is a full second set of fetches in this cube. Inspired by myself, there are four copies of [[Lore Seeker]]. More Lore Seekers means more chances to open power, and that's kinda fun.

---

#### Draft Experience

Similar to MTGO Vintage Cube, this is a 540 cube usually drafted with three packs of 15. I chose these for three reasons:

1. To ease the introduction of players already familiar with the MTGO Vintage Cube to No Limit Vintage.
2. To increase the variety of cube decks in comparison to 360 lists.
3. To reduce the consistency in finding A+B combos and increase decision making during draft.

You can draft it any which way though. 4x12 and 5x9 are both common draft options for smaller groups, and 6x9 and 4x20 are both very nice.

Statistically, in a 3x15 draft the four copies of Lore Seeker will add three additional packs. I think. The math got hard and I got stuck.

---

#### Non-Traditional Cards

There are many cards that don't follow the 'normal' rules of magic that you may be unfamiliar with, such as [[Contract from Below|62f96e43-aebd-4de2-969a-37cd1d62f127]], [[Booster Tutor|c3a5b25e-c5af-417e-8675-162ab18ac2b1]], [[The Explorer|1936aa23-3a5d-4386-bc4d-66841e0cab2c]], and others. Explaining the card explains the card, so these are explained in more depth in this primer.

---

#### Aesthetics

With the release of Throne of Eldraine in 2019 and the launch of Secret Lair drops a few months later, Wizards changed the way people consume and perceive Magic cards. Existing premium products like Premium Deck Series, From the Vault, and Masterpieces made way to a wide swath of premium and serialized chase cards in every release. These changes are not for me. I want my Cube to feel like the 1993-2018 era of Magic cards (plus extended art).

For the most part, I adhere to this ordering of printings:

1. Original Print Old Border Foil
2. Judge Promo Old Border Foil
3. Original Print Extended Art Foil
4. Original Print Foil
5. Judge Promo
6. Reprint Old Border Foil
7. Original Print
8. Misc Promos

Some strict additional printing rules.
1. No Borderless cards (unless there is no other printing)
2. No Secret Lair cards (unless there is no other printing)
3. No Etched, Gold-etched, Textured, Silverscreen, Neon Ink, Gilded, Galaxy, Surge, Double-Rainbow, Step-and-compleat, Oil Slick, Halo, Rainbow, Confetti, Invisible ink, Raised, Ripple, Fracture, Mana, First Place, or whatever foil treatment they cook up next.

There are no alters, and few signed cards.

TL;DR - I'm a Magic boomer and I just want kids to get off my lawn.

## House Rules

**Terms**

Game - one game of Magic
Match - a set of games
Event - the draft and all matches
Pregame actions - a catch-all term to describe Conspiracies and Heroes

**Snow Note:**

Players are allowed to add any number of [[Snow-Covered|c835f235-4196-4281-9788-13e5d54a92d0]] lands and [[Wastes|bf10c264-c7f6-4ae3-b3ef-ff12bd7b64c0]] to their deck during deckbuilding. You can figure out why, you're a smart kiddo.

---

#### Rule Clarifications

<<[[!Contract from Below|62f96e43-aebd-4de2-969a-37cd1d62f127]] [[!Blacker Lotus|4c85d097-e87b-41ee-93c6-0e54ec41b174]] [[!Booster Tutor|c3a5b25e-c5af-417e-8675-162ab18ac2b1]] [[!Gleemox|e6d7fba8-a157-4d81-9d6b-bd210a96b248]]>>

If you ante a card and lose the game, your opponent becomes the owner of the card. It is now a part of their limited pool for the duration of the event. Yes, they can immediately sideboard it in against you.

If a card instructs you to rip itself apart, it is instead removed from the match.

If you are instructed to open a booster pack, you may open any Magic booster pack, including any undrafted cube packs. You may open a pack you have previously opened. Cards drafted with Booster Tutor are removed from the event when the game ends. 

Errata: Gleemox is not banned

Reminder: You must present a legal deck at the start of each game.

Conspiracies start the game in the Command Zone. They are not permanents and cannot be interacted with. They do not count towards your deck size. You may play as many conspiracies as you draft.

Hero cards start the game on the Battlefield. They are permanents and can be interacted with. They do not count towards your deck size. You may play as many hero cards as you draft.

## Archetypes

No Limit Vintage is, in many ways, a combo paradise. There are a LOT of combos both intended and unintended present in this cube. Most decks, and most colour combinations, can include a game-winning combo within it's 40, but this does not mean that a combo is necessary to succeed. This cube has seen a lot of success from aggro and midrange strategies. The demands of card strength in this cube (and midrangification of modern card design) have made classical control and tempo harder to draft in this cube, although the archetypes are certainly still viable when the right cards are opened.

Due to the quantity of combos in the cube, every colour needs to be prepared for them. White enjoys copious amounts of anti-combo hatebears, blue is loaded up with counterspells, black doubles down on hand attack, red gets access to efficient creature interaction, and green has both hatebears and efficient permanent removal. Most often, decks are use a combination of colours to address the multi-faceted threats combo decks present.

Mana in this cube is generally very good, when you draft it. The set of double fetches make accessing your triomes and duals very strong, but you absolutely do have to draft fixing. Players frequently make the mistake of assuming that because there are double fetches, they can just pass them and they'll show up later. They usually don't.

---

#### Featured Archetypes

---

Archetypes are listed in the order I thought of them. This is very far from a comprehensive list of archetypes, and drafters regularly surprise me with the archetypes they come up with on the fly during draft.

---

**Boros Aggro**

Boros Aggro regularly appears in the 3-0 bracket of a No Limit Vintage cube draft. No Limit's increased access access to fast mana enable greater numbers of fast mana-juiced aggro decks. Boros has unique access to disruptive hatebears alongside aggressive red creatures, allowing it to easily stumble combo decks by a turn or two. Boros has some of the best reach of any aggressive combination, with Boros five drops providing massive board state and life total swings.

---

**Storm**

I love storm, so I put a ton of storm cards in this cube. Typically, most storm decks draft one or two of [[Bolas's Citadel]], [[Yawgmoth's Will]], and [[Underworld Breach]]. If you're really creative, you might be able to do it without one of these three. There's a ton of black tutors, and as many rituals as I could justify including.

---

**Cheater**

There's literally so many ways to cheat stuff into play in this cube. Blue can [[Show and Tell]], [[Tinker]], and [[Flash]]. Red can [[Sneak Attack]], [[Volatile Chimera]], and [[Through the Breach]]. Green can [[Oath of Druids]], [[Natural Order]], and [[Channel]]. Black can reanimate like, six different ways. Decks that revolve around putting a lot of mana worth of permanents into play for very little cost are regularly very successful.

No two cheater decks are the same, but Reanimator and Flash are two of the more well known and well defined cheater combo decks. There's plenty of ways to layer these combos into other decks, especially with one card combos like Volatile Chimera.

---

**Artifacts**

Artifacts come in a few different flavours. The most common are the [[Time Vault]] artifact combo decks and big mana [[Tolarian Academy]] decks. These decks pick up lots of cheap artifacts to pay off things like [[Urza's Saga]], [[Urza, Lord High Artificer]], and [[Karn, Scion of Urza]]. [[Retrofitter Foundry]] and [[Candelabra of Tawnos]] are very strong assets to the artifact decks.

---

**Creature Combo**

Creature combo is underexplored in drafts. There's less common combos like [[Hazel's Brewmaster]] with [[Kiki-Jiki, Mirror Breaker]] or [[Devoted Druid]], easily assembled with [[Survival of the Fittest]] or [[Fauna Shaman]]. Traditional [[Splinter Twin]] combos are present, and the one-card combo of [[Arcane Savant]] with [[Trigger Happy]], [[Saw in Half]], or [[Sublime Epiphany]] is very strong when assembled. [[Agatha's Soul Cauldron]] can do a lot of work in creature combo.

---

**Simic Caw**

[[Nadu, Winged Wisdom]] is a ridiculously broken card. [[Lightning Greaves]], [[Bristly Bill, Spine Sower]] and [[Scythecat Cub]] are top enablers for Nadu directly, and can sometimes just win games themselves in the green blue value deck. You'll also find strong synergy with [[Opposition]] and [[Skullclamp]].

---

**Lands**

There's a good amount of lands support in this cube. There's the combo style lands deck with [[Dark Depths]] and [[Fastbond]] + [[Zuran Orb]], as well as value lands with cards that pick up lands ([[Wrenn and Six]]) and cards that play multiple lands ([[The Explorer]]). There are a lot of land tutors in the cube, including staples like [[Crop Rotation]] and [[Golos, Tireless Pilgrim]], as well as unorthodox tutors like [[Park Map]].

---

**Wheels**

There's a bunch of cards that make your opponent draw cards, like [[Timetwister]], [[Wheel of Fortune]], and [[Time Spiral]]. There's a bunch of cards that make your opponents regret drawing cards, like [[Orcish Bowmasters]], [[Hullbreacher]], and [[Leovold, Emissary of Trest]]. Put the two together and things go well.

---

**Izzet Tempo**

The only regularly successful true tempo deck is Izzet Tempo. Cards like [[Counterspell]], [[Lightning Bolt]], and [[Snapcaster Mage]] make up the base of this type of deck. You can expand on the core strategy by layer in a [[Splinter Twin]] package, picking up midrange bombs like [[Inzerva, Master of Insights]], or focus on Delving to victory with cards like [[Treasure Cruise]], [[Abhorrent Oculus]], and [[Murktide Regent]]


---

## Excluded Cards

**A note on pregame actions**

Pregame actions have a density problem. Too many, and games are determined by how many pregame actions a player has. I want pregame actions to add power, complexity, and nuance to a Vintage Cube experience, not redefine the cube experience around them. To avoid an overwhelming amount of pregame actions, the magic number for No Limit Vintage is around 10 to 15. I've selected the ones I believe are most powerful, with the following exceptions.

---

<<[[!Power Play|bbfca319-edc4-45f2-b208-35c8112ec918]][[!Backup Plan|84c5a45a-adc2-41f9-893c-58a03bebbf0c]][[!The Vanquisher|08a63083-997b-4a72-af48-cd35e6e9599d]][[!Advantageous Proclamation|f8c37fe8-43b3-454e-a70b-5b0d0f396a33]]>>

**Power Play, Backup Plan, The Vanquisher, and Advantageous Proclamation**

Selecting your pregame effects, sculpting your deck around the strength of a Conspiracy or Hero, and selecting them during draft are all methods of skill expression No Limit Vintage intends to reward. These four pregame actions test no dimension of skill. I want to ask players interesting and complex questions and these four cards ask nothing of interest.

---

<<[[!Worldknit|7f1fe849-b407-4252-b175-3f4afbbcea1b]][[!Sovereign's Realm|abefb30c-780d-4496-8fc6-6e1b80686c15]]>>

**Worldknit and Sovereign's Realm**

While these conspiracies measure some skill expression in a way the previous pregame actions do not, they remove all skill expression related to mana. When drafting these conspiracies, you are no longer incentivized to read draft signals, identify open lanes, or draft any fixing. This reduction in skill expression is antithetical to the goals of this cube.

---

<<[[!The Philosopher|efbffd56-92a1-4b17-8d53-e9f28b1872e1]] [[!The Provider|d9987b43-7f20-46ce-b7dd-f3126e5bc991]] [[!The Tyrant|be5044ab-5f7d-4109-8574-42306ca86b4c]] [[!Hold the Perimeter|00717f7c-0778-4a02-b6c0-b3c3f07e75a9]]>> 

**The Philosopher, The Provider, The Tyrant, Hold the Perimiter, [[Sentinel Dispatch]], [[The Savant]], and [[The Slayer]]**

These pregame actions cause archetypal imbalance. Each creates a meaningful barrier for aggro decks, providing control, midrange, and combo massive boons to their matchup spread with no cost to deckbuilding. Aggro decks are an important part of the No Limit Vintage environment. With the goal of preserving archetypal diversity, these seven pregame actions are excluded. Notably, [[The Protector]] is sufficiently non-warping as to allow for inclusion in No Limit Vintage.

---

<<[[!Deal Broker|42dc14d0-60e2-419a-a6cf-ba155c51c310]] [[!Canal Dredger|a5365f0d-5e51-4e5d-9385-c4d08882c24f]] [[!Agent of Acquisitions|c57def6f-cc2a-4aec-927b-6a561d9fa7a1]]>>

**Deal Broker, Canal Dredger, and Agent of Acquisitions**

Deal Broker results in players beginning a 'bidding' phase immediately following the end of the draft. This often leads to a chaotic and lengthy negotiation process entirely detracting from the deckbuilding portion of the cube. TL:DR; people yapped too much.

Canal Dredger is a powerful card that comes with a cost to draft overhead. As players conclude their drafts, they have to pass cards around the table to get them to the Canal Dredger player, and verifying they got all the right cards. It's just kinda annoying but maybe this guy comes back at some point.

Agent of Acquisitions allows a player to identify when a given pack has enough beneficial cards to take all of them. The cost is that player is now sitting out the entire rest of the pack. It's boring AF and nobody likes doing it, even if it's optimal.

---
